00:31.798 --> 00:34.631
<i>Everyone thinks Harlem</i>
<i>was the capital of jazz in the 1930s.</i>

00:36.136 --> 00:40.334
<i>That all of New York flooded uptown</i>
<i>at night to party till dawn.</i>

00:40.507 --> 00:44.443
<i>Nice story, but unfortunately,</i>
<i>it's just not true.</i>

00:44.611 --> 00:48.741
<i>It was all happening in the little town</i>
<i>of Passaic, New Jersey.</i>

00:50.116 --> 00:52.448
<i>Passaic was the capital of jazz</i>
<i>in the '20s and '30s...</i>

00:52.619 --> 00:55.053
<i>... because of its own native son...</i>

00:55.221 --> 00:56.916
<i>... Thomas "Fats" Waller...</i>

00:57.090 --> 00:59.752
<i>... one of the greatest entertainers</i>
<i>of all time.</i>

00:59.926 --> 01:02.394
<i>Chapter 1, the birth of Fats Waller.</i>

01:02.562 --> 01:06.862
<i>It all began right here,</i>
<i>a hundred years ago...</i>

01:07.033 --> 01:09.501
<i>... in Passaic, New Jersey.</i>

01:09.669 --> 01:11.432
<i>Right here, on this block.</i>

01:11.604 --> 01:13.731
<i>It was a different neighborhood then,</i>
<i>but look here...</i>

01:13.907 --> 01:15.568
<i>... he was born at 261 Main Street.</i>

01:15.742 --> 01:18.575
<i>When he was young, he used to follow</i>
<i>his father around the streets...</i>

01:18.745 --> 01:21.009
<i>... because his father</i>
<i>was a street minister.</i>

01:21.181 --> 01:24.947
<i>He started playing piano, as I understand,</i>
<i>out in the streets here in Passaic...</i>

01:25.118 --> 01:26.142
<i>... on a harmonium.</i>

01:26.319 --> 01:29.777
<i>Poor boy put on pounds</i>
<i>faster than the price of aluminum.</i>

01:29.956 --> 01:33.119
<i>One-forty-seven.</i>

01:33.293 --> 01:35.784
<i>Thomas, you're gonna break</i>
<i>Dr. Benton 's scale.</i>

01:35.962 --> 01:37.452
<i>You're getting worse.</i>

01:37.630 --> 01:41.157
<i>Maybe that's why he would have to play</i>
<i>a very huge instrument.</i>

01:41.334 --> 01:43.996
<i>So he would spend nights here,</i>
<i>at the great organ.</i>

01:44.170 --> 01:46.764
<i>Fats used the church</i>
<i>as his training ground.</i>

01:46.940 --> 01:50.842
<i>And soon, all of Passaic</i>
<i>would know his name.</i>

01:51.010 --> 01:53.376
<i>Fats lived his life all in excess.</i>

01:53.546 --> 01:58.142
<i>Loads of music, loads of food</i>
<i>and loads of women.</i>

01:58.318 --> 02:03.051
<i>Who would expect a simple influenza virus</i>
<i>would get him in his bed?</i>

02:03.223 --> 02:04.952
<i>A sleeping-train bed, though.</i>

02:05.125 --> 02:09.925
<i>But still, the train had been stopped</i>
<i>in the freezing cold winter...</i>

02:10.096 --> 02:12.690
<i>... in the train station in Kansas City.</i>

02:12.866 --> 02:16.029
<i>Fats, are you okay? Fats? You okay?</i>

02:17.704 --> 02:20.229
<i>Is there a doctor on the train?</i>

02:25.078 --> 02:28.946
<i>Fats was the star</i>
<i>that made the whole town shine.</i>

02:39.225 --> 02:41.693
Hey, Jerry, hand me Number 9.

02:43.429 --> 02:46.694
<i>I will give you</i>

02:46.866 --> 02:49.926
- Okay. All right.
<i>- Number 9</i>

02:50.503 --> 02:51.993
<i>Handing you number</i>

02:52.172 --> 02:54.106
- Would you shut up?
<i>- Number 9</i>

02:55.308 --> 02:57.503
Could you just paint
and be quiet, please?

02:57.677 --> 02:59.167
Knock it off.

03:00.480 --> 03:02.505
It's terrible.

03:10.190 --> 03:12.886
- What the duck, Jerry?
- What?

03:13.059 --> 03:15.357
I asked you to give me Number 9,
the nose.

03:15.528 --> 03:16.722
Yeah, that's what I did.

03:16.896 --> 03:19.831
No, you didn't. This is Number 6.
This is the eye.

03:19.999 --> 03:23.264
All right, well, how am I supposed to tell
the difference between a six and a nine?

03:23.436 --> 03:25.961
Because we did both the eyes already,
you doofus.

03:26.139 --> 03:27.163
Come on, get organized.

03:27.340 --> 03:29.604
I told you, put the finished ones
in a separate pile.

03:29.776 --> 03:31.243
Look, what's the difference, man?

03:31.411 --> 03:34.403
A nostril and an upside-down eye
are the same anyway. It looks fine.

03:34.581 --> 03:38.483
Oh, is that supposed to be funny?
Are you trying to say Fats had big nostrils?

03:38.651 --> 03:41.176
- Jerry.
- Hi, officer, how's it going?

03:41.354 --> 03:44.517
Look what happened. Last night,
some hoodlums came and did...

03:44.691 --> 03:46.625
- Oh, really?
...all this stuff here, this...

03:46.793 --> 03:49.284
- Here we go again.
- It's disgusting.

03:49.462 --> 03:52.397
- I hate graffiti.
- Yeah, they even left the ladder.

03:52.565 --> 03:54.931
That's, like, evidence.
We should confiscate it.

03:55.101 --> 03:57.467
- Catch them.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah. Sure.

03:57.637 --> 03:59.468
You're getting on my nerves.

03:59.639 --> 04:02.836
You keep this up,
you'll be spending the night in jail.

04:03.009 --> 04:05.000
- Okay.
- Moron.

04:05.178 --> 04:07.373
If... If they come back for the ladder,
we'll catch them.

04:07.547 --> 04:11.449
Hey, fellas, is that supposed to be
Biggie Smalls or something?

04:11.618 --> 04:14.644
No, man, that's that dead old blues guy,
Louis Armstrong.

04:14.821 --> 04:18.154
No, my ignorant little buddies,
this is Fats Waller.

04:18.324 --> 04:20.224
- Really?
- Famous <i>jazz</i> musician.

04:20.392 --> 04:23.851
He was born in my building
about a hundred years ago.

04:28.701 --> 04:30.328
<i>- Ice cream, anyone?</i>
<i>- Oh, yeah.</i>

04:30.503 --> 04:32.835
That's what I'm talking about.

04:34.641 --> 04:36.506
Mr. Fletcher, you know,
really, seriously...

04:36.676 --> 04:39.201
...if you don't like the painting,
you can... You can tell me.

04:39.379 --> 04:43.281
I know that there's something wrong
with the nose, I don't know if you noticed.

04:44.250 --> 04:45.979
What about the authorities, Mike?

04:46.152 --> 04:48.882
The city already has issues
with the building as it is.

04:49.055 --> 04:51.489
Mr. Fletcher, you don't have
to worry about the police.

04:51.658 --> 04:54.627
- I worked my magic on them.
- Yeah, he did confuse them.

04:54.794 --> 04:56.785
Okay, they think some gangsters did it.

04:56.963 --> 04:58.988
- And you confused them?
- Yeah, with my finesse.

04:59.165 --> 05:02.191
Yeah, I feel great. You sure
this is gonna bring us more customers?

05:02.368 --> 05:05.565
I hope so. I mean, anyway, don't you think
it's time the people around here...

05:05.738 --> 05:09.139
...started to learn a bit little about, you
know, the history of their neighborhood?

05:09.309 --> 05:11.709
I mean, people don't even know
who Fats is.

05:11.878 --> 05:14.574
- It's a little embarrassing.
- Hey. Hey. That's not true.

05:15.248 --> 05:17.546
- We know who Fats Waller is.
- Is that right?

05:17.717 --> 05:19.981
Bet you can't sing a <i>jazz</i> song.

05:20.153 --> 05:23.054
- Oh, challenge.
- Uh-oh. Uh-oh.

05:24.824 --> 05:25.950
That's not <i>jazz.</i>

05:26.125 --> 05:27.183
<i>Fuzzy, oh, oh</i>

05:27.360 --> 05:31.319
<i>Fuzzy wuzzy was a bear</i>
<i>Fuzzy jazzy had no hair</i>

05:31.497 --> 05:33.829
<i>Fuzzy wuzzy wasn't fuzzy, was he?</i>

05:34.000 --> 05:37.595
<i>Yes, he was, he was Fuzzy</i>
<i>Had a fuzzy face</i>

05:37.770 --> 05:42.070
<i>Check this out and let me say</i>
<i>One thing to you</i>

05:42.241 --> 05:44.709
<i>Watch me play my fuzzy bass</i>

05:48.981 --> 05:50.039
Standup bass.

05:53.386 --> 05:54.751
I'm sorry, Mr. Fletcher.

05:54.921 --> 05:56.445
It's all right, Jerry. I got it.

05:56.622 --> 05:58.214
Actually, you gotta go back to work.

05:58.391 --> 06:00.723
Duty calls. You gotta
go back to the microwave.

06:00.893 --> 06:02.793
I think I saw one of your creations
just roll by.

06:02.962 --> 06:05.055
- Turn the microwave on high.
- You think it's a joke?

06:05.231 --> 06:07.756
Let me tell you, you're gonna
be responsible for my brain tumor.

06:07.934 --> 06:10.129
- All of you guys are.
- Where the hell is Jerry?

06:10.303 --> 06:11.531
Man, what's her problem?

06:11.704 --> 06:14.036
She said she wanted a sporty car,
now she's freaking out.

06:14.207 --> 06:15.299
You did that?

06:19.178 --> 06:21.806
- I don't want this.
- Don't forget your salad bowl.

06:21.981 --> 06:24.176
I told you she wouldn't be
into them big pipes.

06:24.350 --> 06:26.079
Polish or not, she's still a girl.

06:26.252 --> 06:28.618
Come on, Wilson.
She couldn't get the doors open.

06:28.788 --> 06:31.222
Well, she could have went through
the window.

06:31.891 --> 06:34.086
These damn helmets.

06:34.260 --> 06:36.888
I don't think they're helping
with the microwaves at all.

06:37.063 --> 06:38.394
Oh, you'll thank me.

06:38.564 --> 06:41.499
- All right, I'll see you in the morning.
- All right, thanks.

06:57.483 --> 06:59.917
Good night, Mike.
Don't forget to turn out the lights.

07:00.086 --> 07:01.951
Good night, Mr. Fletcher.

07:16.769 --> 07:19.499
<i>A rent party was the place to be</i>
<i>in the '20s and '30s.</i>

07:19.672 --> 07:20.696
They were jumping.

07:20.873 --> 07:22.932
If you didn't have enough money
to cover your rent...

07:23.109 --> 07:27.307
...you'd invite a few musicians,
charge for drinks, and you'd get it on.

07:27.480 --> 07:29.948
Everybody would throw
just a little bit in the pot.

07:30.116 --> 07:31.981
<i>A dollar, whatever they could spare.</i>

07:32.151 --> 07:34.585
Jerry doesn't believe you've ever been
to a rent party, Mr. Fletcher.

07:34.754 --> 07:36.779
What are you talking about?
I never said that.

07:36.956 --> 07:38.287
Oh, man, I used to go to all of them.

07:38.458 --> 07:40.619
That's where I'd meet
all the girls on Saturday night.

07:40.793 --> 07:43.353
I can't imagine you with a girl,
Mr. Fletcher.

07:43.529 --> 07:46.657
Oh, nice, that's great. That's perfect.

07:46.833 --> 07:48.266
Yeah, what about you, Jerry?

07:48.434 --> 07:51.961
I don't see much action
coming out of your trailer at night.

07:52.138 --> 07:55.369
When I was your age,
my balls were flapping so hard...

07:55.541 --> 07:58.305
... I had to scrape them off the ground
and beg them to come home with me.

07:58.478 --> 08:00.878
- Come on, balls.
- Yeah, come on.

08:01.047 --> 08:03.106
Come on. That's hilarious.

08:03.282 --> 08:04.306
What about you, Mike?

08:04.484 --> 08:06.418
When was the last time you heard
some action coming out of his room?

08:06.586 --> 08:08.076
Why are you all worried about me for?

08:08.254 --> 08:09.949
I heard some action sometime.

08:10.122 --> 08:13.523
Now, it's more like a trumpet solo.

08:15.595 --> 08:16.653
Trumpet solo.

08:16.829 --> 08:18.763
Could you close your mouth
when you chew? Thanks.

08:18.931 --> 08:20.660
How come you never got married,
Mr. Fletcher?

08:20.833 --> 08:24.496
Well, the common story is...

08:24.670 --> 08:27.901
...the girl that you was gonna ask,
you waited too long to ask...

08:28.074 --> 08:30.406
...and she went on
and married somebody else.

08:30.576 --> 08:33.669
And then you can't find anybody
that compared to her.

08:33.846 --> 08:36.746
So, what happens? You get old.

08:46.292 --> 08:48.817
Obviously we're looking
at a real improvement in quality of life.

08:48.995 --> 08:50.963
These brand-new condominiums
are gonna bring us...

08:51.130 --> 08:53.155
...the fresh blood
that we need for our community...

08:53.332 --> 08:56.199
...and transform this slum forever.

08:56.369 --> 08:59.702
<i>"Slum"?</i> Hey, this is not a slum.

08:59.872 --> 09:03.899
Hey, sure, the place needs a few repairs,
but I'm taking care of it.

09:04.076 --> 09:06.203
Look, look,
business is about to pick up.

09:06.379 --> 09:07.607
I can feel it.

09:07.780 --> 09:10.943
I'm sorry, Mr. Fletcher,
but the building is condemned.

09:11.117 --> 09:14.883
It violates structural,
fire and plumbing standards.

09:15.054 --> 09:17.818
I don't see wheelchair access.

09:17.990 --> 09:19.753
Your video store is a tenement.

09:20.426 --> 09:23.554
You have 60 days from this notice
of demolition...

09:23.729 --> 09:26.698
...to bring it up to code,
otherwise we will have to demolish it.

09:26.866 --> 09:28.857
- But we will relocate you...
- Yes.

09:29.035 --> 09:31.936
...to a property
of proportionate fair-market value.

09:32.104 --> 09:33.662
Projects aren't so bad, you know.

09:33.839 --> 09:35.739
Move to the projects?

09:38.177 --> 09:39.667
How am I gonna tell Mike?

09:39.845 --> 09:43.941
Look, I just wanna improve the life
of the people of Passaic, that's all.

09:46.986 --> 09:50.547
You know, you don't have to pay me
this month, Mr. Fletcher. I'm okay.

09:50.723 --> 09:54.159
Don't worry about the money, Mike.
I'll pay you soon.

09:54.794 --> 09:59.060
In fact, I... I need for you
to take over for me.

09:59.231 --> 10:01.290
- You're retiring?
- Oh, no, no, no.

10:01.467 --> 10:04.231
This year's the 60th anniversary
of Fats' death.

10:04.403 --> 10:07.861
And there's a ceremony
that's being organized in commemoration.

10:08.040 --> 10:10.907
We gonna all get together
in that abandoned train where he died...

10:11.077 --> 10:13.170
...and we're gonna play his records
until morning.

10:13.346 --> 10:15.143
- Oh, wow.
- Yeah.

10:15.314 --> 10:17.111
I wanna come. Can I come with you?

10:17.283 --> 10:18.375
No.

10:18.551 --> 10:20.485
I just told you,
I need you to take over for me.

10:20.653 --> 10:24.612
Oh, right, right. I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
I'm sorry. Okay.

10:24.790 --> 10:27.020
You want me to just run the shop
while you're gone?

10:27.193 --> 10:28.558
You think I could do that?

10:28.728 --> 10:30.457
You tell me.

10:31.030 --> 10:32.622
I'm not gonna let you down,
Mr. Fletcher.

10:33.132 --> 10:34.827
Good, just don't set the place on fire.

10:35.001 --> 10:38.994
Oh, no. Service, quality, safety,
you can count on that.

10:39.171 --> 10:41.036
Excellent.

10:41.207 --> 10:43.334
Here's something really important:

10:43.509 --> 10:44.601
You must never...

10:44.777 --> 10:46.745
Slam the door, because
the building will collapse.

10:46.912 --> 10:50.905
No, Mike. I mean, yes,
but that's not what I wanted to say.

10:51.083 --> 10:53.779
- You must never...
- Use the VCR to rewind the tapes...

10:53.953 --> 10:56.319
No. Why do you always
have to finish my sentences?

10:56.489 --> 10:58.650
- Okay, just listen.
- Okay. I'm sorry. Go ahead.

10:58.824 --> 11:01.657
Okay, you must... Damn it.

11:02.261 --> 11:04.695
Now I forgot what I had to say.

11:04.864 --> 11:07.264
- But it's very...
- Lock the door.

11:07.767 --> 11:09.962
- Mr. Fletcher, have a good trip.
- I'll have a good trip.

11:10.136 --> 11:11.535
Take some pictures and call me.

11:11.704 --> 11:13.228
Oh, yes, yes. I... I remember.

11:14.206 --> 11:15.696
See, you wanted to finish my sentence.

11:15.875 --> 11:19.333
- I lost my focus. I can't...
- No, no. I was listening. I was listening.

11:19.512 --> 11:22.606
Hey, Mike. Mike. Keep Jerry...

11:22.782 --> 11:25.046
I can't hear you.

11:27.086 --> 11:28.610
Keep Jerry out. Out, out.

11:30.723 --> 11:32.418
What? I don't know what that means.

11:32.591 --> 11:35.185
<i>"Peek your edge too.
Peek your <i>edge..."</i></i>

11:35.428 --> 11:40.365
<i>"Tuo. Too. Peek your edge too."</i>

11:40.533 --> 11:42.364
That's what it is.

11:42.768 --> 11:45.737
I just found out something sad today.

11:46.706 --> 11:49.231
Mr. Fletcher can't spell.

11:51.277 --> 11:53.643
Maybe his parents
couldn't afford school.

11:53.813 --> 11:55.508
Did he have parents?

11:56.482 --> 11:58.643
- Yeah.
- Interesting.

11:58.818 --> 12:01.150
Don't mention this to anybody.

12:01.320 --> 12:04.721
- Just keep this between us. Don't...
- Of course not, that would be racist.

12:04.890 --> 12:08.155
Peek your... Pick.

12:08.327 --> 12:09.817
Your age. Pick your age.

12:10.529 --> 12:12.019
He's talking gibberish.

12:12.198 --> 12:14.826
It's nonsense, but it's not his fault.

12:16.335 --> 12:19.031
The power plant's controlling us.
I know it.

12:19.205 --> 12:21.139
- Through microwaves.
- Mm-hm.

12:21.307 --> 12:24.071
They're using it to make us do things.

12:24.243 --> 12:26.438
To buy things, to accept things.

12:26.612 --> 12:28.978
And who...? Who...? Who are they?
Who are "they"?

12:29.148 --> 12:31.981
The government, the FBI, of course.

12:32.151 --> 12:34.745
- And I say no more.
- Right.

12:34.920 --> 12:37.047
I'm gonna sabotage
the power plant tonight...

12:37.223 --> 12:38.588
...and you're gonna help me.

12:38.758 --> 12:41.318
Look, I got a map.
Completely worked out.

12:41.494 --> 12:43.621
We short-circuit this
with whatever that thing is.

12:43.796 --> 12:45.661
And that blows up the transformer.

12:45.831 --> 12:47.492
All we gotta do is climb the fence...

12:47.666 --> 12:51.500
...and throw this sweet grappling hook
right into the transformer. Boom.

12:52.004 --> 12:53.266
You know what I mean?

12:53.439 --> 12:55.031
Yeah.

12:55.207 --> 12:57.607
This, my friend, is your camouflage.

12:57.777 --> 12:59.074
Camouflage.

12:59.245 --> 13:00.269
Bones.

13:00.446 --> 13:01.811
We need that electricity.

13:01.981 --> 13:05.144
You know, we got the machines, we...
And nobody rewinds the tapes.

13:05.317 --> 13:07.251
- This is more important than that.
- You gotta rewind the tapes.

13:07.419 --> 13:09.011
That's the lamest excuse
I've ever heard.

13:09.188 --> 13:11.952
It's totally non-sequitury,
what you're saying to me.

13:12.124 --> 13:13.955
- It's a lame excuse?
- Yeah, it's lame.

13:14.126 --> 13:16.321
Really? And the power plant
is controlling us?

13:16.495 --> 13:18.122
That's not nonsense?
That's not paranoia?

13:18.297 --> 13:20.390
Okay, it sounds crazy,
and you know why?

13:20.566 --> 13:22.966
- Because it's affecting my brain too.
- Mm-hm.

13:23.135 --> 13:24.159
It's paranizing it.

13:24.336 --> 13:27.271
Mr. Fletcher left me
in charge of the store.

13:27.439 --> 13:30.237
Me. He trusted me with the store.
Do you know what that means?

13:30.409 --> 13:33.378
No, actually I don't.
Maybe you could explain it to me.

13:33.546 --> 13:35.138
- It means that I'm not doing this.
- What?

13:35.314 --> 13:36.611
- I'm not doing this with you.
- Okay.

13:36.782 --> 13:38.443
So you'll just do anything
Mr. Fletcher says...

13:38.617 --> 13:40.551
...even though, by the way,
he's not your real father.

13:40.719 --> 13:42.550
- So... So what?
- And he's completely illiterate.

13:42.721 --> 13:44.018
- He's not...
- But you won't do anything for me...

13:44.190 --> 13:45.919
...your best friend,
who has a melting brain.

13:46.091 --> 13:49.527
Can l...? Can l...? Can I help you
make a selection? Because if not...

13:49.695 --> 13:52.823
... I'm gonna have to ask you
to make space for the other customers.

13:53.332 --> 13:55.425
Oh, sorry, I didn't <i>realize</i>
it was rush hour.

13:55.601 --> 13:57.000
I won't bother you anymore.

13:57.169 --> 14:00.195
You know, it does get busy unexpectedly.

14:00.372 --> 14:01.805
And you know, he's not illiterate.

14:01.974 --> 14:04.772
First of all, because if he was illiterate,
smart guy...

14:04.944 --> 14:06.468
... he wouldn't be able to write:

14:06.645 --> 14:08.476
<i>"Peek your edge too."</i>

14:08.647 --> 14:11.810
Which is... It's probably Buddhist
or something.

14:11.984 --> 14:13.781
It's like... Like a chant.

14:13.953 --> 14:16.387
<i>"Peek your... Pick your edge too."</i>

14:16.889 --> 14:18.823
<i>- Smart guy.</i>
- I'm not saying he's illiterate.

